in the journal Cell Metabolism:
A Cell Press Journal,

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:17.160
excellent journal.

00:03:17.160 --> 00:03:20.900
And the title of the paper
is "Fasting Blood Glucose

00:03:20.900 --> 00:03:24.477
as a Predictor of Mortality:
Lost in Translation".

00:03:24.477 --> 00:03:26.740
And I'll explain what
the "Lost in Translation"

00:03:26.740 --> 00:03:27.736
part means in a moment.

00:03:27.736 --> 00:03:29.827
But the basic takeaway of this study,

00:03:29.827 --> 00:03:30.900
and I should mention that

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:33.763
the first author of the
study is Palliyaguru,

00:03:33.763 --> 00:03:34.596
PALLIYAGURU, guru,

00:03:38.734 --> 00:03:40.317
Palliyaguru, et al.

00:03:42.770 --> 00:03:45.960
The basic finding of the
study is that in humans,

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.960
higher blood glucose is
associated with mortality.

00:03:51.402 --> 00:03:54.300
And in fact, if you look at blood glucose,

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.610
resting blood glucose across the lifespan,

00:03:56.610 --> 00:03:58.087
what you find is as people age,

00:03:58.087 --> 00:04:00.850
resting blood glucose goes up.

00:04:00.850 --> 00:04:02.110
Now, this is very interesting,

00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:04.330
because for a long time it was thought

00:04:04.330 --> 00:04:06.950
that metabolism actually
goes down as we age.

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:08.423
And to some extent, that's true,

00:04:08.423 --> 00:04:10.640
but the reductions in metabolism

00:04:10.640 --> 00:04:13.000
are not nearly as robust
as we once thought

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.080
that they were across the lifespan.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:17.604
However, unless there's something done

00:04:17.604 --> 00:04:20.730
to mitigate the increase
in blood glucose associated

00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:21.870
with the aging,

00:04:21.870 --> 00:04:24.309
almost everybody experiences a gradual,

00:04:24.309 --> 00:04:28.280
but regular increase in
resting blood glucose

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:30.370
that predicts mortality.

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:31.730
Now, the title, as I mentioned,

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:34.720
is "Fasting Blood Glucose
as a Predictor of Mortality:

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:35.767
Lost in Translation".

00:04:35.767 --> 00:04:38.630
And the reason that they
included "Lost in Translation"

00:04:38.630 --> 00:04:40.768
in the title is that what I just told you,

00:04:40.768 --> 00:04:43.180
that increases in resting blood

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:46.300
glucose predict mortality, or
are correlated with mortality,

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:47.858
is true for human beings

00:04:47.858 --> 00:04:50.607
and for non-human primates, monkeys.

00:04:50.607 --> 00:04:53.163
But the opposite is true in mice.

00:04:53.163 --> 00:04:54.970
And so I thought it was important

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:57.122
to use this study as an example

00:04:57.122 --> 00:04:59.647
of where it studies in mice often,

00:04:59.647 --> 00:05:02.249
but not always, translate to humans

00:05:02.249 --> 00:05:04.230
and to non-human primates.

00:05:04.230 --> 00:05:05.500
So today, I'm going to be careful

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:07.150
to distinguish when a study

00:05:07.150 --> 00:05:09.010
was performed in mice versus in humans,

00:05:09.010 --> 00:05:13.424
because it seems that at
least when discussing feeding,

00:05:13.424 --> 00:05:15.606
blood glucose and other aspects of diet

00:05:15.606 --> 00:05:17.659
as they relate to health and wellbeing,

00:05:17.659 --> 00:05:20.340
whether or not a study
was performed in rodents

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:23.960
or in humans can be very important.

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:24.800
In this case,

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:27.335
