00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:15.790
what it is that we're talking about

00:14:15.790 --> 00:14:17.450
when we talk about nutrition.

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:19.320
I'm going to give you an example

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:21.760
of a study that was
published a few years ago,

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:24.580
2018, by a colleague of mine at Stanford,

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:28.940
Chris Gardner, he's a terrific professor

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:30.826
of nutrition and has done a lot

00:14:30.826 --> 00:14:33.843
of important studies on
how nutrition impacts

00:14:33.843 --> 00:14:35.863
different aspects of health.

00:14:35.863 --> 00:14:38.020
This is a large-scale study.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:39.660
It was published in JAMA,

00:14:39.660 --> 00:14:41.650
the Journal of the American
Medical Association,

00:14:41.650 --> 00:14:45.690
one of the very top tier
journals in the area of medicine,

00:14:45.690 --> 00:14:47.680
and certainly for a paper on nutrition

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:49.170
to show up there meant that it had

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:51.821
to meet an exceedingly high standard.

00:14:51.821 --> 00:14:56.260
This paper, where Chris
is the first author,

00:14:56.260 --> 00:14:58.872
it's Gardner et al, 2018 JAMA,

00:14:58.872 --> 00:15:03.643
looked at weight loss
in people following one

00:15:03.643 --> 00:15:06.703
particular diet versus
another particular diet.

00:15:06.703 --> 00:15:09.550
And this was a 12 month weight loss study.

00:15:09.550 --> 00:15:11.777
So it was focused
specifically on weight loss,

00:15:11.777 --> 00:15:14.610
although they looked at some
other parameters as well.

00:15:14.610 --> 00:15:16.329
And the basic conclusion of the study was

00:15:16.329 --> 00:15:19.450
that there was no significant difference

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:22.410
in weight change between
people following a healthy,

00:15:22.410 --> 00:15:24.042
low fat diet versus a healthy,

00:15:24.042 --> 00:15:26.011
low carbohydrate diet with significantly

00:15:26.011 --> 00:15:28.459
more dietary fats in them.

00:15:28.459 --> 00:15:31.217
This caused a lot of ripples

00:15:31.217 --> 00:15:35.060
in the world of nutrition
and nutritional science,

00:15:35.060 --> 00:15:36.957
and certainly in the general population,

00:15:36.957 --> 00:15:40.110
because anyone that understands diet

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:42.970
and nutrition would
immediately say, but wait,

00:15:42.970 --> 00:15:45.268
there are all sorts of
different implications of eating

00:15:45.268 --> 00:15:48.637
one type of diet, say low
carbohydrate, higher fats,

00:15:48.637 --> 00:15:51.545
versus a higher
carbohydrate, lower fat diet.

00:15:51.545 --> 00:15:53.148
And indeed there are.

00:15:53.148 --> 00:15:55.202
This study was focused specifically

00:15:55.202 --> 00:15:58.607
on fat loss and on weight loss.

00:15:58.607 --> 00:16:03.400
So as we discuss time restricted feeding,

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:04.254
we need to be very precise

00:16:04.254 --> 00:16:07.690
about what are the effects
of time restricted feeding,

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:09.820
and of eating in particular ways

00:16:09.820 --> 00:16:13.180
at particular times, we are
going to emphasize again,

00:16:13.180 --> 00:16:15.940
whether or not the study was
done in mice or in humans,

00:16:15.940 --> 00:16:18.500
in athletes, in men, in women, or both,

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:20.357
but the study from Gardner and colleagues

00:16:20.357 --> 00:16:21.715
is a beautiful study,

00:16:21.715 --> 00:16:23.337
and really emphasizes that

00:16:23.337 --> 00:16:26.863
if one's main goal is
simply to lose weight,

00:16:26.863 --> 00:16:31.601
then it really does not
matter what one eats provided

00:16:31.601 --> 00:16:34.653
that the number of calories burned

00:16:34.653 --> 00:16:38.180
is higher than the number
of calories ingested.

00:16:38.180 --> 00:16:41.930
However, anyone out there who understands

00:16:41.930 --> 00:16:43.655
a little bit of biology,

00:16:43.655 --> 00:16:46.000
or a lot of biology will agree

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:47.272
that there are many factors

00:16:47.272 --> 00:16:50.687
that impact that calories
burned part of the equation.

00:16:50.687 --> 00:16:52.400
Some of those are obvious.

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:53.337
So for instance,

00:16:53.337 --> 00:16:57.910
amount of exercise, type of
exercise, basal metabolic rate,

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:00.039
how much energy one
burns just sitting there.

00:17:00.039 --> 00:17:01.398
I've talked before on this podcast

00:17:01.398 --> 00:17:04.800
about NEIT, Non Exercise
Induced Thermogenesis,

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:06.969
where if people bounce around
a lot and fidget a lot,

00:17:06.969 --> 00:17:11.060
they can burn anywhere from
800 to 2,000 calories per day.

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:13.142
So their quote-unquote
basal metabolic rate

00:17:13.142 --> 00:17:14.680
is actually much higher simply

00:17:14.680 --> 00:17:15.620
because they're fidgeters,

00:17:15.620 --> 00:17:17.360
whereas people who tend
to be more stationary

00:17:17.360 --> 00:17:19.850
have a lower basal
metabolic rate, on average.

00:17:19.850 --> 00:17:22.249
There's a great science to support this.

00:17:22.249 --> 00:17:25.030
Metabolic factors and hormones

00:17:25.030 --> 00:17:26.750
are also very important.

00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:28.746
Hormones, such as thyroid hormone

00:17:28.746 --> 00:17:31.370
and insulin and growth hormone,

00:17:31.370 --> 00:17:33.577
and the sex story to hormones,
testosterone and estrogen,

00:17:33.577 --> 00:17:36.197
those levels will also
profoundly influence

00:17:36.197 --> 00:17:39.341
the calories out, the
calories burned component

00:17:39.341 --> 00:17:42.161
of the calories in, calories out equation.

00:17:42.161 --> 00:17:45.450
So if out there on the internet

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:47.199
or in listening to a particular podcast

00:17:47.199 --> 00:17:48.817
or speaker, somebody says,

00:17:48.817 --> 00:17:50.527
this is the ideal diet,

00:17:50.527 --> 00:17:53.310
or calories in, calories out does not

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:54.850
matter, or calories in calories out

00:17:54.850 --> 00:17:56.054
is the only thing that matters.

00:17:56.054 --> 00:17:58.130
I think it's very important to understand

00:17:58.130 --> 00:18:00.010
that there are some foundational truths,

00:18:00.010 --> 00:18:01.990
such as calories in, calories out,

00:18:01.990 --> 00:18:03.286
but that of course,

00:18:03.286 --> 00:18:06.750
hormone factors and the context in which

00:18:06.750 --> 00:18:09.226
a given diet regimen is taking place

00:18:09.226 --> 00:18:11.210
are exceedingly important.

00:18:11.210 --> 00:18:14.160
A good example of this would be puberty

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:16.180
at that time in life,

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:18.220
sex steroid hormones
are changing profoundly

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:21.260
in the body as our growth
hormone and other hormones.

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:23.330
And much of caloric intake

00:18:23.330 --> 00:18:25.679
is directed towards protein synthesis,

00:18:25.679 --> 00:18:27.900
towards the production of muscle and bone

00:18:27.900 --> 00:18:29.230
and other tissues of the body.

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:31.140
And that's because of changes in hormones

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:32.530
that we call puberty.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:35.200
So, there's no way that we can drill

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:38.700
into every aspect of a given feeding plan

00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:42.440
or feeding schedule that would allow us

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:44.360
to tap into every aspect of the list

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:46.720
that I read out before weight loss,

00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:48.700
fat loss, muscle organ, genome, epigenome,

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:50.802
inflammation, exercise,
cognition, mood, and lifespan.

00:18:50.802 --> 00:18:53.110
But today, we're going to be very precise

00:18:53.110 --> 00:18:55.378
about how time restricted feeding,

00:18:55.378 --> 00:18:58.500
it's very clear from both animal studies

00:18:58.500 --> 00:18:59.382
and human studies

00:18:59.382 --> 00:19:03.433
can have a very powerful
and positive impact

00:19:03.433 --> 00:19:05.660
on everything from weight loss

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:09.189
and fat loss to various health parameters.

00:19:09.189 --> 00:19:11.040
This is a beautiful literature

00:19:11.040 --> 00:19:14.428
that's emerged mostly in
the last 10 or 15 years.

00:19:14.428 --> 00:19:16.710
And as we march into this literature,

00:19:16.710 --> 00:19:18.166
what you'll see is that there actually

00:19:18.166 --> 00:19:22.602
is a perfect diet for you on a given day.

00:19:22.602 --> 00:19:24.684
And that perfect diet for you on

00:19:24.684 --> 00:19:27.850
a given day is contextual,

00:19:27.850 --> 00:19:30.017
meaning it depends on
what you did yesterday

00:19:30.017 --> 00:19:32.960
and what you're going to do tomorrow.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:34.556
So there is a perfect diet for you.

00:19:34.556 --> 00:19:35.900
And today, I'm going to arm you

00:19:35.900 --> 00:19:38.170
with the mechanisms and understanding

00:19:38.170 --> 00:19:39.620
that will allow you to define what

00:19:39.620 --> 00:19:41.020
that perfect diet is

00:19:41.020 --> 00:19:43.728
and will allow you to eat on a schedule

00:19:43.728 --> 00:19:46.260
and to eat the things that are going

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:47.641
to best serve your goals.

00:19:47.641 --> 00:19:51.400
So let's talk about eating
and what happens when you eat,

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:54.380
and let's talk about
