Satchin and colleagues have collected

02:14:59.881 --> 02:15:04.881
regular placement of the eating
window or feeding window,

02:15:05.770 --> 02:15:08.300
every 24 hours is important.

02:15:08.300 --> 02:15:11.140
You don't have to be absolutely
rigid and neurotic about

02:15:11.140 --> 02:15:11.973
this,

02:15:11.973 --> 02:15:13.840
but you don't want it sliding
around on the weekends so that

02:15:13.840 --> 02:15:16.302
it starting two hours later
and ending two hours later,

02:15:16.302 --> 02:15:18.154
a couple days a week,

02:15:18.154 --> 02:15:22.695
because then you start to offset
many of the positive health

02:15:22.695 --> 02:15:25.700
effects that have been
demonstrated for time restricted

02:15:25.700 --> 02:15:26.798
feeding.

02:15:26.798 --> 02:15:31.798
Remember if you eat your
food within a certain feeding

02:15:32.166 --> 02:15:35.599
window, but that feeding window
shifts by a couple of hours,

02:15:35.599 --> 02:15:38.926
it is effectively like
jet lagging your system.

02:15:38.926 --> 02:15:42.364
It is effectively like traveling
a couple times zones over

02:15:42.364 --> 02:15:45.698
eating there for a few days
and coming back when in fact

02:15:45.698 --> 02:15:48.421
you're not traveling,

02:15:48.421 --> 02:15:50.481
that's because of the
way that food adjusts,

02:15:50.481 --> 02:15:52.700
the circadian clock genes.

02:15:52.700 --> 02:15:55.520
Now you can offset some of
that through the use of light.

02:15:55.520 --> 02:15:58.140
And I've talked extensively
about how to use light in

02:15:58.140 --> 02:15:59.537
previous podcasts, but again,

02:15:59.537 --> 02:16:01.970
early morning and all day bright,

02:16:01.970 --> 02:16:04.510
light exposure as safely as
you can, ideally from sunlight,

02:16:04.510 --> 02:16:06.010
not through a window, et cetera,

02:16:06.010 --> 02:16:07.840
avoiding bright light in
the middle of the night,

02:16:07.840 --> 02:16:10.610
extremely important for mood offsetting,

02:16:10.610 --> 02:16:12.404
metabolic dysfunction, et cetera,

02:16:12.404 --> 02:16:16.283
not incidentally Satchin's early work was,

02:16:16.283 --> 02:16:20.910
he was one of the three
co-discoverers of the cells in the

02:16:20.910 --> 02:16:23.390
eye, the so-called melanopsin
cells that set the central

02:16:23.390 --> 02:16:26.230
circadian clock. So he was
a pioneer in that field,

02:16:26.230 --> 02:16:28.930
which led him to be a pioneer
in this field and so on.

02:16:29.828 --> 02:16:34.337
When should that eight hour
window be placed within each 24

02:16:34.337 --> 02:16:37.107
hour cycle? Well, let's
talk about ideal ideal.

